        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Grande Archimedi geometrica[e], ac machinalis scientia[e] testimonium M. Marcelli contigit; interdicto, cum 
                        Syracusa[e] caperentur, ne violaretur vnus; nisi fefellisset imperium militaris imprudentia. Plinius. L. 7. c. 37. 
                        Naturalis historia[e]. De artium plurimarum excellentia, Astrologia, grammatica, </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                    <person name="Archimedes"/>
                    <person name="Pliny the Elder"/>
                    <book title="Natural History"/>
                    <location name="Syracuse"/>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>medicina, geometria, architectura.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"M. Marcellus, too, at the taking of Syracuse, offered a remarkable homage to the sciences of geometry and mechanics, 
                by giving orders that Archimedes was to be the only person who should not be molested; his commands, however, were disregarded, 
                in consequence of the imprudence of one of the soldiers." Pliny, bk. 7, ch. 37, of the Natural history [Trans. Bostock and Riley]. 
                About the superiority of the most powerful arts: astrology, grammar, medicine, geometry, architecture.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="ab ignaro milite quis esset, interfectum" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Vnicus Archimedes, interfectus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Archimedes"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The unsurpassed Archimedes killed.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Eccè tandem Romana virtus vicit Gra[e]cam artem. Nec temerè increbuit. Ponat omnia virtus. Sed qualis Marcelli virtus, id est, 
                        animosa, strenua, pra[e]potens; eademq[ue] constanter inuicta.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Behold, at last Roman valor has overcome Greek skill; and it grew with good cause. Let valor subject everything, 
                but valor such as that of Marcellus, namely spirited, vigorous, and very powerful and invariably unshaken.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
